<subSubSection lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="42" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
See the note above under 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Croton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Croton cassinioides" order="Malpighiales" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cassinioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Croton cassinioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its synonym 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. delphinianus" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" rank="species" species="delphinianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">C. delphinianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
regarding the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Scott-Elliot 1557</emphasis>
specimen (P00133052, upper right), which was 
<pageBreakToken pageId="42" pageNumber="43" start="start">also</pageBreakToken>
cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Baillon, H" journalOrPublisher="Adansonia" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="B5" refString="Baillon, H, 1891a. Liste des plantes de Madagascar. Bulletin Mensuel de la Societe Linneenne de Paris 2: 926-928, 966-968, 977-979." title="Liste des plantes de Madagascar. Bulletin Mensuel de la Societe Linneenne de Paris 2: 926 - 928, 966 - 968, 977 - 979." year="1891 a">Baillon (1891a)</bibRefCitation>
as a syntype of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lasiopyrus" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="lasiopyrus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. lasiopyrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Croton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Croton cassinioides" order="Malpighiales" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cassinioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Croton cassinioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lasiopyrus" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" rank="species" species="lasiopyrus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. lasiopyrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sufficiently different that they are not easily confused; the former has smaller (1.5-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.7-3 cm) elliptic leaves with dentate to subentire margins and grows in littoral zones near sea level, while the latter has larger (4-15.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-7 cm) obovate leaves with entire margins and grows in moist montane forests.
</paragraph>
